  "text": "## Java Bytecode to JIT Compiled Code Chain in OpenJDK\n\n### Compilation Request Phase\nCompilation begins when `CompileBroker::compile_method()` (compileBroker.cpp:1365) is invoked with method, OSR bytecode index, and compilation level. This method performs prerequisite checks and class resolution, then calls `CompileBroker::compile_method_base()` (compileBroker.cpp:1154) which queues the compilation task for execution by a compiler thread.\n\n### C2 Compiler Entry Point\nWhen a compiler thread processes the queued task, it invokes `C2Compiler::compile_method()` (c2compiler.cpp:117). This method initializes compilation options including flags for escape analysis, lock elimination, and SuperWord vectorization. It instantiates a `Compile` object, which is the core compilation engine.\n\n### Bytecode Parsing and Ideal Graph Construction\nThe `Compile` constructor (compile.cpp:613) orchestrates the entire compilation. During the parsing phase (lines 744-828), it:\n1. Creates a `Parse` object via `CallGenerator::generate()` which invokes the parser\n2. The `Parse` constructor (parse1.cpp:402) initializes bytecode parsing state and resets the bytecode iterator\n3. `Parse::do_one_block()` (parse1.cpp:1502) implements the main bytecode parsing loop, processing each bytecode instruction sequentially\n4. Each bytecode is converted to intermediate representation (IR) nodes forming the Ideal graph\nThe Parser uses helper methods in `parse2.cpp` and `parse3.cpp` for specific bytecode types (arithmetic, array access, etc.) and `parseHelper.cpp` for common operations.\n\n### Optimization Phase\nAfter parsing completes, `Compile::Optimize()` (compile.cpp:2209) applies numerous optimization phases including:\n- Constant folding and algebraic simplification\n- Dead code elimination\n- Loop optimization\n- Escape analysis for scalar replacement\n- Inlining optimization\nThese transformations convert the Ideal graph into optimized machine-independent code.\n\n### Code Generation and Installation Phase\n`Compile::Code_Gen()` (compile.cpp:2906) performs machine-specific code generation:\n1. `Matcher::match()` converts Ideal nodes to machine instructions\n2. `PhaseCFG` builds control flow graph and performs global code motion\n3. `PhaseChaitin` allocates registers to variables\n4. Post-allocation expansion and peephole optimization refine the code\n\nFinally, `PhaseOutput::Output()` (output.cpp:266) converts nodes to machine code bytes in a buffer, and `PhaseOutput::install()` (output.cpp:3399) invokes `install_code()`.\n\n### Code Cache Installation\n`PhaseOutput::install_code()` (output.cpp:3413) calls `ciEnv::register_method()` (ciEnv.cpp:973) which:\n1. Validates compilation dependencies and checks for class state changes\n2. Calls `nmethod::new_nmethod()` (nmethod.cpp:1122) to create a compiled method object\n3. The nmethod constructor allocates space in the code cache\n4. `nmethod::post_init()` (nmethod.cpp:1257) finalizes the nmethod and calls `CodeCache::commit()` (codeCache.cpp) to atomically install the compiled code into the code cache where the JVM can execute it\n\nThe nmethod object acts as a wrapper containing compiled machine code, metadata, deoptimization information, and exception handlers, making it executable by the JVM's runtime system."
}

